This article is a presidential proclamation by Barack Obama declaring January 17, 2011, as the Martin Luther King, Jr., Federal Holiday. The proclamation commemorates the 25th anniversary of the holiday and celebrates the life and legacy of Dr. King. It emphasizes Dr. King's dedication to justice and equality and calls on Americans to continue his work by expanding access to opportunity and ending structural inequalities. The proclamation also encourages Americans to participate in a national day of service to honor Dr. King's vision of unity and community.